    "content_descriptors": {
      "ids": [
        5
      ],
      "notes": "Ludus: A Gladiator Story is a text-based narrative game set in ancient Rome. It contains the following mature content:\r\n\r\nViolence. The game depicts arena combat, physical injury, and death. Violence is described through prose rather than shown graphically, there are no gore animations or explicit imagery. Players make choices that can result in killing opponents, witnessing executions, and suffering serious wounds. The tone is unflinching but not gratuitous.\r\n\r\nSlavery and dehumanisation. The game's central subject is the experience of enslaved people in Roman society. This includes depictions of forced labour, physical punishment, humiliation, and the systematic denial of personhood. These themes are treated with seriousness and are core to the story's meaning.\r\n\r\nPolitical oppression and systemic cruelty. The game portrays a society in which power is used to exploit and control. Characters in positions of authority behave with cruelty, corruption, and indifference to suffering.\r\nGrief, despair, and loss of agency. Some story paths explore themes of hopelessness, the death of loved ones, and situations where the player has no good options. These moments are intentional and serve the narrative.\r\n\r\nAlcohol. Wine and drinking are referenced in dialogue and prose as part of the historical setting. Consumption is implied rather than depicted.\r\n\r\nThere is no sexual content, drug use, or self-harm in the game."
    }
  },
